² That this is here the meaning of aedituus is shown by the Table of Chapters, where it is represented by ostiarius. The office of aedi- tuus in the pagan temple, however, corresponds rather to that of custos in the Christian church (see Chapter I, above), being a position of some dignity. Ausonius, Commemorat-io Professorum Burdigalen- sium, x, 22—30‚ speaks of Phoebicius, a professor who had been Beleni aedituus. DuCange gives the definition “ AEDITUUS, Ostiarius‚ gradus ecclesiasticus; cui aedis sacrae custodia incumbit, custos '': an impossible one, since ostiarius and custos are quite different officials. The word never really became naturalized in Christian literature. Paulinus of Nola uses it, it is true (Epistolae, i, 10; in Migne's Patro- logia Latina, vol. lxi, col. 158); but he was a friend and correspondent of Ausonius.
